            <h2><strong>Waist-to-Hip Ratio (WHR)</strong></h2>
            <p>
                WHR is a measure of your body fat distribution, calculated by dividing the circumference of your waist by the circumference of your hips.
                A high WHR indicates that more fat is stored around the waist, which can be a risk factor for certain health conditions. Remember that it is always best to consult with a healthcare professional for an accurate assessment of your health
            </p> 
            <p>
                <h3>How is WHR calculated?</h3> <br>
                To calculate your WHR, you will need to measure the circumference of your waist and hips. 
                You can use a measuring tape to measure the widest part of your waist, and the widest part of your hips, usually at the level of the buttocks. 
                Once you have these measurements, you can use the following formula: 
                <strong>WHR = waist circumference / hip circumference</strong><br>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <h3>How to measure waist and hip circumference?</h3><br>
                Stand with your feet 25-30 cm apart and distribute your weight evenly on both feet. 
                Use a tape measure to measure your waist and hip circumference, making sure the tape measure is slightly loose to avoid compressing the skin. 
                To measure your waist, place the tape measure at the midpoint between your lowest rib and the top of your hip bone. 
                To measure your hip circumference, place the tape measure around the widest part of your hips.
            </p>
            <p>
                <h3>What can WHR tell us about our health?</h3><br>
                A high WHR can indicate a higher risk for health problems such as heart disease, stroke, and type 2 diabetes.  
                This is because storing excess fat around the waist can increase the production of certain hormones and lead to insulin resistance.  
                In general, a WHR of 0.85 or higher in women, and 0.90 or higher in men, is considered to be high and may indicate an increased risk for health problems. <br>
